30
00:04:38,987 --> 00:04:41,657
Tracks? What are you, Pocahontas?

31
00:04:42,824 --> 00:04:44,243
Come on.

32
00:04:52,042 --> 00:04:54,253
Let's take a look inside.

33
00:05:11,979 --> 00:05:13,981
Teddy.

34
00:05:14,106 --> 00:05:18,235
Don't believe his lies.
He is the one. Kill him.

35
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:20,362
I've finally found him.

36
00:05:20,487 --> 00:05:22,614
How long have I been looking?

37
00:05:23,824 --> 00:05:25,826
Find anything?

38
00:05:26,285 --> 00:05:28,328
Didn't think so.

39
00:05:28,453 --> 00:05:29,746
Let's go, huh?

40
00:05:29,872 --> 00:05:32,124
Oh, fuck this.

41
00:05:33,292 --> 00:05:34,918
You're gonna pay for what you did.

42
00:05:35,794 --> 00:05:38,755
Beg forgiveness and then you pay.

43
00:05:42,509 --> 00:05:45,429
You don't have a clue, you freak!

44
00:05:45,554 --> 00:05:49,308
Beg my wife's forgiveness
before I blow your brains out.

45
00:05:49,433 --> 00:05:52,352
Leonard, you don't know what's going on.

46
00:05:52,477 --> 00:05:54,897
- You don't even know my name.
- Teddy.

47
00:05:55,022 --> 00:05:57,149
Cos you read it off a fucking picture.

48
00:05:57,274 --> 00:06:00,527
<font color="#40a040">[breathless]</font> You don't know who you are.

49
00:06:00,652 --> 00:06:05,157
- I'm Leonard Shelby from San Francisco.
- That's who you were. That's not…

50
00:06:05,282 --> 00:06:07,159
… what you've become.

51
00:06:07,284 --> 00:06:10,537
- Shut your mouth.
- You want to know, Lenny? Come on.

52
00:06:10,954 --> 00:06:12,956
Come on, let's go down to the basement.

53
00:06:13,081 --> 00:06:16,001
Let's go down, you and me together.

54
00:06:16,126 --> 00:06:19,254
Then you'll know who you really are.

55
00:06:22,549 --> 00:06:24,551
- <font color="#40a040">[Teddy]</font> No!
- <font color="#40a040">[gunshot]</font>

56
00:06:26,220 --> 00:06:28,222
It's just an anonymous room.

57
00:06:28,347 --> 00:06:30,807
There's nothing in the drawers.
But you look anyway.

58
00:06:30,933 --> 00:06:33,352
Nothing except the Gideon Bible,…

59
00:06:33,477 --> 00:06:37,314
… which I, of course, read religiously.
<font color="#40a040">[laughs]</font> Hm.

60
00:06:37,439 --> 00:06:41,360
You know who you are
and you know kind of all about yourself.

61
00:06:42,528 --> 00:06:47,366
But just for day-to-day stuff,
notes are really useful.

62
00:06:47,866 --> 00:06:52,454
Sammy Jankis had the same problem
but he really had no system.

63
00:06:52,579 --> 00:06:56,875
He wrote himself a ridiculous amount
of notes but he'd get them all mixed up.

64
00:06:57,000 --> 00:06:59,086
You really do need a system if…

65
00:06:59,211 --> 00:07:01,213
… if you're gonna make it work.

66
00:07:52,306 --> 00:07:54,308
<font color="#40a040">[presses bell]</font>

67
00:07:56,143 --> 00:07:58,020
- Hi.
- Hi.

68
00:07:58,145 --> 00:08:01,356
- I'm Mr Shelby from 304.
- What can I do for you, Leonard?

69
00:08:01,481 --> 00:08:03,317
- Um…
- Burt.

70
00:08:03,442 --> 00:08:06,737
Burt. I'm not sure, I think
I may have asked you to hold my calls.

71
00:08:06,862 --> 00:08:09,656
- You don't know?
- I'm not too good on the phone.

72
00:08:09,781 --> 00:08:12,534
You said you like to look people in the eye
when you talk to them.

73
00:08:12,659 --> 00:08:13,911
Yeah, yeah.

74
00:08:14,036 --> 00:08:17,831
- You don't remember saying that.
- I have this condition.

75
00:08:17,956 --> 00:08:20,292
- A condition?
- It's my memory.

76
00:08:20,417 --> 00:08:23,003
- Amnesia?
- No, no, it's different from that.

77
00:08:23,128 --> 00:08:27,299
I have no short-term memory.
I know all about myself, I just…

78
00:08:27,424 --> 00:08:31,220
Since my injury I can't make
new memories. Everything fades.

79
00:08:31,345 --> 00:08:34,848
If we talk for too long
I'll forget how we started…

80
00:08:34,973 --> 00:08:37,643
… and next time I see you
I won't remember this conversation.

81
00:08:37,726 --> 00:08:40,187
I don't even know if I've met you before.

82
00:08:40,479 --> 00:08:44,358
So if I seem a little strange
or rude, or something, uh…

83
00:08:45,359 --> 00:08:47,861
I've told you this before, haven't I?

84
00:08:47,986 --> 00:08:52,032
I don't mean to mess with you
but it's so weird.

85
00:08:52,157 --> 00:08:54,326
- You don't remember me at all?
- No.

86
00:08:54,409 --> 00:08:57,246
- We've talked a bunch of times.
- I'm sure we have.

87
00:08:58,372 --> 00:09:00,374
What's the last thing you remember?

88
00:09:00,624 --> 00:09:02,626
My wife.

89
00:09:03,001 --> 00:09:05,003
What's it like?

90
00:09:09,132 --> 00:09:11,134
It's like waking.

91
00:09:11,468 --> 00:09:13,637
It's like you just woke up.

92
00:09:14,304 --> 00:09:16,306
That must suck.

93
00:09:16,431 --> 00:09:18,016
It's all backwards.

94
00:09:18,141 --> 00:09:21,019
Like, maybe you got an idea
about what you want to do next…

95
00:09:21,144 --> 00:09:23,313
… but you don't remember
what you just did.

96
00:09:23,438 --> 00:09:25,983
I mean, I'm exactly the opposite…

97
00:09:26,066 --> 00:09:29,152
- How long have I been staying here?
- Couple of days.

98
00:09:29,278 --> 00:09:31,697
- And you're holding my calls?
- Like you said.

99
00:09:31,822 --> 00:09:34,199
OK, but this guy's an exception.

100
00:09:34,283 --> 00:09:35,659
You know this guy?

101
00:09:37,160 --> 00:09:40,956
- Yeah, it's your friend, right?
- What makes you think that?

102
00:09:41,081 --> 00:09:43,375
- I saw you together, that's all.
- He's not my friend.

103
00:09:43,500 --> 00:09:44,877
OK.

104
00:09:45,002 --> 00:09:48,672
If he calls or shows up here,
give me a call in my room, OK?

105
00:09:48,755 --> 00:09:50,799
- What, his name's Teddy?
- Teddy, yeah.

106
00:09:50,924 --> 00:09:52,718
All right.

107
00:09:53,135 --> 00:09:56,013
Look, I hope my condition's
not gonna be a problem for you.

108
00:09:56,138 --> 00:09:58,473
Not as long as you remember
to pay the bill.

109
00:09:59,141 --> 00:10:01,143
Yeah. OK.

110
00:10:01,268 --> 00:10:02,561
Forty.

111
00:10:04,396 --> 00:10:05,814
This guy.

112
00:10:07,733 --> 00:10:08,901
He's here already.

113
00:10:10,903 --> 00:10:12,696
Lenny!

114
00:10:13,906 --> 00:10:17,993
You really need a system
if you're gonna make it work.

115
00:10:18,076 --> 00:10:22,623
You kinda learn to trust your handwriting.
It becomes an important part of your life.

116
00:10:22,748 --> 00:10:26,668
You write yourself notes.
Where you put them is really important.

117
00:10:26,793 --> 00:10:29,463
You need a jacket that's got,
like, six pockets,…

118
00:10:29,546 --> 00:10:31,632
… particular pockets
for particular things.

119
00:10:31,757 --> 00:10:36,094
You just kinda learn to know where
things go and how the system works.

120
00:10:36,220 --> 00:10:38,555
You have to be wary of other people
writing stuff foryou…

121
00:10:38,680 --> 00:10:41,725
… that is not going to make sense
or is gonna lead you astray.

122
00:10:41,808 --> 00:10:44,019
I don't know what makes people
take advantage…

123
00:10:44,144 --> 00:10:46,146
… of somebody with this condition.

124
00:10:46,230 --> 00:10:50,150
If you have a piece of information
which… is…

125
00:10:50,776 --> 00:10:54,863
… vital, writing on your body instead of
on a piece ofpaper can be the answer.

126
00:10:54,988 --> 00:10:56,990
It's a permanent way of keeping a note.

127
00:10:57,115 --> 00:10:59,117
<font color="#40a040">[phone rings]</font>

128
00:11:04,164 --> 00:11:05,958
Who is this?

129
00:11:13,549 --> 00:11:16,468
Remember Sammy Jankis.

130
00:11:28,397 --> 00:11:29,356
<font color="#40a040">[door opens]</font>

131
00:11:45,956 --> 00:11:48,250
- Sir, you left these at your table.
- Thanks.

132
00:11:49,334 --> 00:11:51,378
Ah, Lincoln Street?

133
00:11:51,503 --> 00:11:53,297
Just go straight out on Sixth Street,…

134
00:11:53,422 --> 00:11:55,549
- … go east through town…
- I'm gonna write this down.

135
00:11:55,674 --> 00:11:58,927
- Oh, it's easy. Go straight out…
- Trust me, I need to write this down.

136
00:12:05,893 --> 00:12:07,895
The Discount Inn.

137
00:12:31,710 --> 00:12:33,712
Discount Inn.

138
00:12:34,546 --> 00:12:36,548
Natalie.

139
00:12:38,175 --> 00:12:39,927
My car.

140
00:12:41,678 --> 00:12:43,680
Teddy.

141
00:12:56,568 --> 00:12:58,570
John Edward Gammell.

142
00:13:00,489 --> 00:13:02,241
This guy told me his name was Teddy.

143
00:13:07,204 --> 00:13:09,122
Don't believe his lies.

144
00:13:15,838 --> 00:13:17,840
<font color="#40a040">[dials]</font>

145
00:13:19,633 --> 00:13:21,635
<font color="#40a040">[ringing tone]</font>

146
00:13:24,471 --> 00:13:26,473
- Yeah?
- Mr Gammell?

147
00:13:26,598 --> 00:13:28,600
- Lenny, is that you?
- John Gammell?

148
00:13:28,725 --> 00:13:31,103
Lenny, it's Teddy.
Stay there. I'll be right over.

149
00:13:31,228 --> 00:13:34,273
- OK. I'll be waiting.
- <font color="#40a040">[line goes dead]</font>

150
00:14:32,748 --> 00:14:34,750
White male.

151
00:14:35,876 --> 00:14:38,003
First name, John.

152
00:14:38,128 --> 00:14:41,924
Last name G for Gammell.

153
00:14:46,136 --> 00:14:47,930
Drugs.

154
00:14:48,055 --> 00:14:49,681
License plate.

155
00:14:50,974 --> 00:14:53,185
SG13…

156
00:14:55,646 --> 00:14:57,105
… 7IU.

157
00:15:01,860 --> 00:15:03,862
It's him.

158
00:15:09,409 --> 00:15:11,995
I've found you, you fuck.

159
00:16:13,432 --> 00:16:15,767
You said we talked before.
I don't remember that.

160
00:16:15,893 --> 00:16:17,895
Yeah, but it's not amnesia.

161
00:16:18,020 --> 00:16:20,397
I remember up until my injury,
I just can't make new memories.

162
00:16:20,522 --> 00:16:22,733
So I can't remember talking to you.
What did we talk about?

163
00:16:22,858 --> 00:16:24,860
Oh, Sammy Jankis.

164
00:16:24,985 --> 00:16:27,654
I guess I tell people about Sammy
to help them understand.

165
00:16:27,738 --> 00:16:30,949
Sammy's story helps me understand
my own situation.

166
00:16:31,074 --> 00:16:33,744
Sammy wrote himself
endless amounts of notes.

167
00:16:33,827 --> 00:16:35,662
But he got mixed up.

168
00:16:36,413 --> 00:16:40,167
I have a more graceful solution
to the memory problem.

169
00:16:41,835 --> 00:16:43,837
I'm disciplined and organised.

170
00:16:43,962 --> 00:16:46,715
I use habit and routine
to make my life possible.

171
00:16:47,174 --> 00:16:49,176
Sammy had no drive,…

172
00:16:49,301 --> 00:16:51,303
… no reason to make it work.

173
00:16:51,887 --> 00:16:52,846
Me?

174
00:16:53,764 --> 00:16:55,349
Yeah,…

175
00:16:55,474 --> 00:16:57,476
… I got a reason.

176
00:17:09,238 --> 00:17:11,240
<font color="#40a040">[activates alarm]</font>

177
00:17:14,785 --> 00:17:17,829
Today, 1pm, meet Natalie for info.

178
00:17:19,039 --> 00:17:23,210
She has also lost someone.
She will help you out ofpity.

179
00:17:40,352 --> 00:17:42,771
- Natalie.
- You don't remember me.

180
00:17:42,896 --> 00:17:45,566
- I should've explained. I have this cond…
- You did explain, Lenny.

181
00:17:46,316 --> 00:17:49,278
Please call me Leonard.
My wife called me Lenny.

182
00:17:49,361 --> 00:17:52,948
- I know, you told me.
- Then I probably told you I hated it.

183
00:17:53,031 --> 00:17:54,950
Yeah.

184
00:17:55,075 --> 00:17:57,953
Do you mind taking your glasses off?
It's hard for me to…

185
00:17:59,538 --> 00:18:00,330
Thanks.

186
00:18:00,455 --> 00:18:03,000
So, you have information for me?

187
00:18:03,125 --> 00:18:05,836
- Is that what your little note says?
- Yeah.

188
00:18:05,961 --> 00:18:09,381
Must be tough living your life
according to a couple of scraps of paper.

189
00:18:09,506 --> 00:18:12,926
Mix your laundry list with your grocery list
and you'll end up eating your underwear.

190
00:18:14,511 --> 00:18:16,763
I guess that's why you have
those freaky tattoos.

191
00:18:17,222 --> 00:18:19,474
Yeah, it's tough. It's almost impossible.

192
00:18:20,601 --> 00:18:24,062
Look, I'm sorry I don't remember you.
It's nothing personal.

193
00:18:27,065 --> 00:18:29,735
I do have information for you.

194
00:18:30,152 --> 00:18:32,362
You gave me a license-plate number.

195
00:18:33,155 --> 00:18:35,908
Had my friend at DMV trace it.

196
00:18:36,158 --> 00:18:37,826
Guess what name came up?

197
00:18:39,161 --> 00:18:42,414
John Edward Gammell. John G.

198
00:18:42,539 --> 00:18:43,790
Do you know him?

199
00:18:43,916 --> 00:18:47,628
No. But his face on his driver's licence
looked really familiar.

200
00:18:47,753 --> 00:18:50,380
I think he's been in the bar, maybe.

201
00:18:50,506 --> 00:18:53,926
Here's a copy of his licence,
his registration, photo and all.

202
00:18:54,009 --> 00:18:56,053
Are you sure you want this?

203
00:18:56,178 --> 00:18:58,847
- Have I told you what this man did?
- Yeah.

204
00:18:58,972 --> 00:19:01,266
Well, then you shouldn't have to ask.

205
00:19:01,391 --> 00:19:03,602
Even if you get revenge,
you're not gonna remember it.

206
00:19:03,727 --> 00:19:05,729
You're not even gonna know it happened.

207
00:19:05,854 --> 00:19:09,149
My wife deserves vengeance. It doesn't
make any difference if I know about it.

208
00:19:09,274 --> 00:19:11,568
Just because
there are things I don't remember…

209
00:19:11,693 --> 00:19:13,987
… doesn't make my actions meaningless.

210
00:19:14,071 --> 00:19:17,574
The world doesn't just disappear
when you close your eyes.

211
00:19:17,741 --> 00:19:21,370
Anyway, maybe I'll take a photograph
to remind myself.

212
00:19:21,495 --> 00:19:23,497
Get another freaky tattoo.

213
00:19:27,793 --> 00:19:30,003
Tell me about her again.

214
00:19:31,046 --> 00:19:32,464
Why?

215
00:19:32,589 --> 00:19:35,300
Because you like to remember her.

216
00:19:37,219 --> 00:19:39,221
She was beautiful.

217
00:19:40,806 --> 00:19:43,016
- To me she was perfect.
- No.

218
00:19:43,141 --> 00:19:45,978
Don't just recite the words.

219
00:19:47,020 --> 00:19:50,482
Close your eyes and remember her.

220
00:20:01,159 --> 00:20:03,161
You can just feel the details.

221
00:20:05,956 --> 00:20:09,209
The bits and pieces
you never bothered to put into words.

222
00:20:13,797 --> 00:20:16,842
And you can feel these extreme moments.

223
00:20:16,925 --> 00:20:18,719
Even if you don't want to.

224
00:20:21,430 --> 00:20:24,391
You put these together
and you get the feel of a person.

225
00:20:26,935 --> 00:20:28,854
Enough to know
how much you miss them.

226
00:20:35,068 --> 00:20:39,156
And how much you hate the person
who took them away.

227
00:20:48,207 --> 00:20:51,418
I, um, I added an address in here.

228
00:20:51,543 --> 00:20:54,963
It might be useful.
It's an abandoned place outside of town.

229
00:20:55,088 --> 00:20:57,966
Um, I guy I knew
used to do bigger deals there.

230
00:21:00,302 --> 00:21:02,095
It's isolated.

231
00:21:02,221 --> 00:21:04,223
Sounds perfect.

232
00:21:06,892 --> 00:21:10,062
- Do I owe you any…
- I wasn't helping you for money.

233
00:21:10,187 --> 00:21:12,356
- I'm sorry.
- It's OK.

234
00:21:12,439 --> 00:21:14,525
See, you have this condition.

235
00:21:16,610 --> 00:21:20,531
You still staying at the Discount Inn?
Room 304? Left it at my place.

236
00:21:25,744 --> 00:21:27,538
Yeah.

237
00:21:29,498 --> 00:21:32,209
- They treating you OK?
- I don't remember.

238
00:21:35,128 --> 00:21:37,130
You know what we have in common?

239
00:21:39,174 --> 00:21:41,510
We are both survivors.

240
00:21:44,972 --> 00:21:46,974
You take care, Leonard.

241
00:22:14,626 --> 00:22:16,837
Remember Sammy Jankis.

242
00:22:17,880 --> 00:22:22,009
I met Sammy through work. Insurance.
I was an investigator.

243
00:22:22,134 --> 00:22:24,595
I'd investigate the claims
to see which ones were phoney.

244
00:22:24,720 --> 00:22:26,722
I had to see through people's bullshit.

245
00:22:26,847 --> 00:22:29,516
It was useful experience
cos now it's my life.

246
00:22:29,600 --> 00:22:32,895
When I meet someone,
I don't know if I've met them before.

247
00:22:32,978 --> 00:22:35,439
I have to look in their eyes
and try and figure them out.

248
00:22:35,564 --> 00:22:38,817
My job taught me the best way to find out
what someone knew was let them talk.

249
00:22:38,942 --> 00:22:40,777
Watch the eyes and the body language.

250
00:22:40,903 --> 00:22:44,948
If someone scratches their nose,
experts tell you it means they're lying.

251
00:22:45,073 --> 00:22:48,535
It really means they're nervous. People
get nervous for all sorts of reasons.

252
00:22:48,660 --> 00:22:49,828
It's all about context.

253
00:22:49,953 --> 00:22:51,955
Yeah, I was good.

254
00:22:52,080 --> 00:22:55,083
Sammy was my first real challenge.

255
00:22:56,627 --> 00:22:58,420
<font color="#40a040">[engine starts]</font>

256
00:23:01,590 --> 00:23:04,801
Yo, Lenny! I thought you'd split for good.

257
00:23:04,927 --> 00:23:07,304
- Well, things change.
- So I see.

258
00:23:07,429 --> 00:23:10,474
- My name's Teddy.
- I guess I've told you about my condition.

259
00:23:10,599 --> 00:23:14,561
Only every time I see ya.
Come on, I'll buy you lunch.

260
00:23:20,234 --> 00:23:22,444
- Have I told you about Sammy Jankis?
- Mmm. Yeah.

261
00:23:22,569 --> 00:23:24,571
I'm sick of hearing about the guy.

262
00:23:24,696 --> 00:23:26,865
What about John G?
You think he's still here?

263
00:23:26,990 --> 00:23:29,535
- Who?
- Johnny G, the guy you're looking for.

264
00:23:29,660 --> 00:23:32,079
- That's why you haven't left town, right?
- Maybe.

265
00:23:32,204 --> 00:23:35,457
- Leonard, you have to be very careful.
- Why?

266
00:23:35,582 --> 00:23:38,627
You mentioned that maybe somebody
was trying to set you up.

267
00:23:38,752 --> 00:23:40,295
Get you to kill the wrong guy.

268
00:23:40,420 --> 00:23:43,966
I go on facts, not recommendations,
but thank you.

269
00:23:44,091 --> 00:23:47,094
Lenny, you can't trust a man's life
to your little notes and pictures.

270
00:23:47,219 --> 00:23:49,972
- Why not?
- Because your notes could be unreliable.

271
00:23:50,097 --> 00:23:51,765
- Memory's unreliable.
- Oh, please.

272
00:23:51,890 --> 00:23:55,519
No, really. Memory's not perfect,
it's not even that good. Ask the police.

273
00:23:55,644 --> 00:23:58,021
Eyewitness testimony is unreliable.

274
00:23:58,146 --> 00:24:00,607
The cops don't catch a killer
by sitting around remembering stuff.

275
00:24:00,732 --> 00:24:03,694
- They collect facts and draw conclusions.
- That's not what I'm saying.

276
00:24:03,819 --> 00:24:05,946
Facts, not memories.

277
00:24:06,071 --> 00:24:08,365
That's how you investigate.
I know, it's what I used to do.

278
00:24:08,490 --> 00:24:12,411
Memory can change the shape of a room,
it can change the colour of a car.

279
00:24:12,744 --> 00:24:14,913
And memories can be distorted.

280
00:24:15,038 --> 00:24:17,040
They're an interpretation, not a record.

281
00:24:17,165 --> 00:24:19,209
They're irrelevant if you have the facts.

282
00:24:19,334 --> 00:24:22,296
You really want to get this guy, don't you?

283
00:24:22,421 --> 00:24:25,924
He killed my wife.
He took away my fucking memory.

284
00:24:27,885 --> 00:24:30,429
He destroyed my ability to live.

285
00:24:33,348 --> 00:24:34,725
You're living.

286
00:24:35,767 --> 00:24:37,561
Only for revenge.

287
00:24:37,936 --> 00:24:39,938
Well, then we'll get the bastard.

288
00:24:40,063 --> 00:24:42,191
Where are you staying?

289
00:24:44,860 --> 00:24:49,198
The Discount Inn. I don't know what room.
I haven't got my key.

290
00:24:49,323 --> 00:24:51,491
Probably left it in your room.

291
00:25:03,128 --> 00:25:04,087
<font color="#40a040">[rings bell]</font>

292
00:25:05,589 --> 00:25:06,715
Hi.

293
00:25:06,840 --> 00:25:09,051
I'm checked in here
but I think I've misplaced my key.

294
00:25:09,176 --> 00:25:13,388
How you doing, Leonard?
Probably in the room, right?

295
00:25:32,115 --> 00:25:34,618
- I don't see my key anywhere.
- Oh, shit. This is the wrong room.

296
00:25:34,743 --> 00:25:36,578
You're in 304. I'm sorry. I fucked up.

297
00:25:36,703 --> 00:25:39,456
- This is not my room?
- No. Come on, let's go.

298
00:25:39,581 --> 00:25:41,416
Then why is this my handwriting?

299
00:25:45,295 --> 00:25:49,550
Well,… this was your room
but now you're in 304.

300
00:25:49,675 --> 00:25:51,885
- When was I in here?
- Last week.

301
00:25:52,010 --> 00:25:55,389
- Then I rented you another room on top.
- Why?

302
00:25:55,514 --> 00:26:00,102
Business is slow, I mean, I told my boss
about your condition and stuff,…

303
00:26:00,227 --> 00:26:01,895
… he said rent him another room.

304
00:26:02,020 --> 00:26:04,231
So how many rooms am I checked into
in this shit hole?

305
00:26:04,356 --> 00:26:06,775
Just two. So far.

306
00:26:06,900 --> 00:26:07,609
Well,…

307
00:26:07,734 --> 00:26:10,320
… at least you're being honest
about ripping me off.

308
00:26:10,445 --> 00:26:14,992
- You're not going to remember anyway.
- You don't have to be that honest, Burt.

309
00:26:15,117 --> 00:26:17,828
Leonard. Always get a receipt.

310
00:26:18,662 --> 00:26:20,956
Oh, yeah. I'll write that down.

311
00:26:23,041 --> 00:26:26,378
- Hey, what time is it?
- Quarter to one.

312
00:26:26,753 --> 00:26:28,547
Excuse me.

313
00:26:28,672 --> 00:26:30,257
Your room's…

314
00:26:43,103 --> 00:26:45,105
- Natalie.
- You don't remember me.

315
00:26:45,480 --> 00:26:48,358
I'd just become an investigator
when I came across Sammy.

316
00:26:48,483 --> 00:26:52,154
Mr Samuel R Jankis, strangest case ever.

317
00:26:52,279 --> 00:26:55,407
The guy's a 58-year-old,
semiretired accountant.

318
00:26:55,532 --> 00:26:57,784
He and his wife were in this car accident,
nothing serious.

319
00:26:57,910 --> 00:27:01,038
But he's acting funny,
he can't get a handle on what's going on.

320
00:27:02,581 --> 00:27:06,210
The doctors find some possible damage
to the hippocampus, nothing conclusive.

321
00:27:06,335 --> 00:27:09,963
Sammy can't remember anything
for more than a couple of minutes.

322
00:27:10,088 --> 00:27:11,465
Can't work, can't do shit.

323
00:27:11,590 --> 00:27:14,801
The medical bills pile up, his wife calls
the insurance company and I get sent in.

324
00:27:16,011 --> 00:27:21,141
This is my first big claims investigation
so I really check into it.

325
00:27:21,266 --> 00:27:24,937
Sammy can think just fine
but he can't make new memories.

326
00:27:25,062 --> 00:27:27,564
He can only remember things
for a couple of minutes.

327
00:27:29,274 --> 00:27:32,486
He'd watch TV but anything longer than
a couple of minutes was too confusing,…

328
00:27:32,611 --> 00:27:34,655
… he couldn't remember how it began.

329
00:27:34,780 --> 00:27:37,074
He liked commercials. They were short.

330
00:27:37,199 --> 00:27:39,076
Sammy. It's time for my shot.

331
00:27:39,201 --> 00:27:42,204
The crazy part was that this guy,…

332
00:27:42,329 --> 00:27:44,831
… who couldn't follow
the plot of Green Acres any more,…

333
00:27:44,957 --> 00:27:47,000
… could do the most complicated things,…

334
00:27:47,125 --> 00:27:49,336
… as long as he learned them
before the accident…

335
00:27:51,839 --> 00:27:54,049
… and as long as he kept his mind
on what he was doing.

336
00:27:55,050 --> 00:27:57,970
The doctors assure me…

337
00:27:58,095 --> 00:28:02,307
… there's a real condition, anterial-grade
memory loss, or short-term memory loss.

338
00:28:02,432 --> 00:28:04,393
It's rare but legit.

339
00:28:05,853 --> 00:28:08,605
But every time I see him,…

340
00:28:08,856 --> 00:28:11,066
… I catch this look,…

341
00:28:11,525 --> 00:28:14,570
… this… slight look of recognition.

342
00:28:15,028 --> 00:28:17,447
But he says he can't remember me at all.

343
00:28:18,115 --> 00:28:20,117
Sammy, it's OK. I got it.

344
00:28:20,534 --> 00:28:22,870
- Hi, Mr Shelby.
- Hi, Mrs Jankis.

345
00:28:22,995 --> 00:28:27,291
Now, I can read people
and I'm thinking ''bad actor''.

346
00:28:27,416 --> 00:28:30,085
So now I'm suspicious
and I order more tests.

347
00:28:33,547 --> 00:28:35,549
Awake.

348
00:28:36,884 --> 00:28:39,553
Oh, where am I?

349
00:28:41,930 --> 00:28:44,183
Somebody's bedroom.

350
00:28:46,018 --> 00:28:48,270
Oh, it must be her room.

351
00:28:49,313 --> 00:28:51,315
But who is she?

352
00:28:59,281 --> 00:29:01,158
It's only me.

353
00:29:03,327 --> 00:29:06,413
- Did you sleep OK?
- Yeah. You?

354
00:29:08,040 --> 00:29:10,042
Oh, shit. Shit.

355
00:29:10,167 --> 00:29:11,877
I gotta be someplace.

356
00:29:15,797 --> 00:29:17,174
It's pretty weird.

357
00:29:18,300 --> 00:29:22,012
It's useful. You never
write a phone number on your hand?

358
00:29:22,137 --> 00:29:26,391
I, um, I should be able
to talk to my friend today…

359
00:29:26,517 --> 00:29:29,561
- … about the license plate.
- Yeah, the license plate.

360
00:29:29,686 --> 00:29:32,105
John G's license plate.

361
00:29:34,983 --> 00:29:36,985
You have it tattooed on your thigh.

362
00:29:55,337 --> 00:29:57,339
Natalie.

363
00:29:59,550 --> 00:30:03,428
She has also lost someone.
She will help you out ofpity.

364
00:30:08,725 --> 00:30:10,644
If it's registered in this state,…

365
00:30:10,769 --> 00:30:13,021
… it should only take a couple seconds
to pull up his licence and registration.

366
00:30:13,146 --> 00:30:15,566
I'll call you as soon as I talk to him.

367
00:30:15,691 --> 00:30:18,610
Could we arrange a meeting now?
I'm not too good on the phone.

368
00:30:27,995 --> 00:30:30,205
You know, it's great that you…

369
00:30:30,455 --> 00:30:32,249
Well, that you're…

370
00:30:32,583 --> 00:30:34,168
… helping me…

371
00:30:34,459 --> 00:30:35,836
… like this.

372
00:30:35,961 --> 00:30:39,256
I'm helping you because you helped me.

373
00:30:51,435 --> 00:30:53,854
So next time you see me,…

374
00:30:53,979 --> 00:30:55,397
… will you remember me?

375
00:31:12,456 --> 00:31:14,666
<font color="#40a040">[softly]</font> I think you will.

376
00:31:15,876 --> 00:31:17,878
<font color="#40a040">[softly]</font> I'm sorry.

377
00:31:20,214 --> 00:31:23,800
Lenny, before you go,
could I have my shirt back, please?

378
00:31:35,437 --> 00:31:37,439
<font color="#40a040">[engine starts]</font>

379
00:31:40,192 --> 00:31:43,070
Yo, Lenny! I thought you'd split for good.

380
00:31:43,403 --> 00:31:46,156
Sammy couldn't pick up
any new skills at all.

381
00:31:46,281 --> 00:31:48,659
But I find something in my research.

382
00:31:48,784 --> 00:31:50,327
Conditioning.

383
00:31:50,452 --> 00:31:53,372
Sammy should still be able to learn
through repetition.

384
00:31:53,497 --> 00:31:56,792
It's how you learn stuff like riding a bike.
You get better through practice.

385
00:31:56,917 --> 00:31:59,127
It's a different part of the brain
from the short-term memory.

386
00:31:59,253 --> 00:32:02,798
So I had the doctors
test Sammy's response to conditioning.

387
00:32:02,923 --> 00:32:07,010
- Pick up any three objects.
- That's a test?

388
00:32:07,135 --> 00:32:09,471
Where were you guys when I did my CPA?

389
00:32:09,596 --> 00:32:10,973
Sorry.

390
00:32:13,183 --> 00:32:14,601
Ta-da!

391
00:32:15,310 --> 00:32:17,521
- <font color="#40a040">[buzz]</font>
- Ow! What the fuck?

392
00:32:17,646 --> 00:32:20,023
- It's a test, Sammy.
- Test this, you fucking quack.

393
00:32:22,693 --> 00:32:25,779
Some of the objects were electrified.
They'd give him a shock.

394
00:32:25,904 --> 00:32:28,991
They kept repeating the test,
always with the same objects electrified.

395
00:32:29,116 --> 00:32:32,536
The point was to see if Sammy could
learn to avoid the electrified objects,…

396
00:32:32,661 --> 00:32:34,872
… not by memory, but by instinct.

397
00:32:43,797 --> 00:32:45,799
<font color="#40a040">[activates alarm]</font>

398
00:32:50,262 --> 00:32:52,264
<font color="#40a040">[knocks on door]</font>

399
00:32:55,642 --> 00:32:58,312
Natalie, right? Who the fuck is Dodd?

400
00:33:00,772 --> 00:33:03,442
Guess I don't have to worry about him
any more.

401
00:33:03,567 --> 00:33:05,485
- What the fuck have you got me into?
- Shh. Come inside.

402
00:33:09,823 --> 00:33:12,743
- Who is he?
- Calm down. OK?

403
00:33:12,868 --> 00:33:16,330
This is my problem. You offered to help.
It's nothing to do with your investigation.

404
00:33:16,455 --> 00:33:17,915
How did you get me into this?

405
00:33:18,040 --> 00:33:20,042
You offered to help me
when you saw what he did to my face.

406
00:33:20,167 --> 00:33:23,670
- How do I know he did that to your face?
- I came straight to you after he did it.

407
00:33:23,795 --> 00:33:26,048
I showed you what he did
and I asked you to help me.

408
00:33:26,173 --> 00:33:29,009
- Oh, and I just take your word?
- Yeah.

409
00:33:29,468 --> 00:33:31,678
Something doesn't feel right.

410
00:33:31,803 --> 00:33:34,181
I think someone's fucking with me,
trying to get me to kill the wrong guy.

411
00:33:34,306 --> 00:33:35,599
- Did you?
- What?

412
00:33:35,724 --> 00:33:37,518
Kill him?

413
00:33:37,726 --> 00:33:41,104
- Course not!
- Hey. Sit down, OK? Sit.

414
00:33:41,855 --> 00:33:46,777
This has nothing to do with you.
You helped me out and I'm grateful.

415
00:33:47,486 --> 00:33:49,196
You have to burn them.

416
00:33:52,783 --> 00:33:56,745
Leonard, you decided to help me.
Trust your own judgement.

417
00:33:56,870 --> 00:34:00,290
You can question everything,
you can never know anything for sure.

418
00:34:00,415 --> 00:34:03,085
- There are things you know for sure.
- Such as?

419
00:34:04,086 --> 00:34:07,756
I know what that's gonna sound like
when I knock on it. <font color="#40a040">[knocks]</font>

420
00:34:07,881 --> 00:34:11,260
I know what that's gonna feel like
when I pick it up. See?

421
00:34:11,385 --> 00:34:14,137
Certainties. It's the kind of memory
you take for granted.

422
00:34:15,722 --> 00:34:18,642
You know, I can remember so much.

423
00:34:19,810 --> 00:34:21,812
The feel of the world…

424
00:34:22,354 --> 00:34:24,356
And her.

425
00:34:30,195 --> 00:34:32,197
She's gone.

426
00:34:32,322 --> 00:34:36,201
And the present is trivia
which I scribble down as fucking notes.

427
00:34:36,326 --> 00:34:38,996
Hey, come on. Try and relax. Come on.

428
00:34:39,079 --> 00:34:42,124
- It's not easy for me to relax.
- Shh. Shhh.

429
00:34:42,416 --> 00:34:44,626
Come on, take your jacket off.

430
00:34:44,751 --> 00:34:47,004
<font color="#40a040">[softly]</font> Here. Come on.

431
00:34:48,505 --> 00:34:50,299
<font color="#40a040">[softly]</font> Hey.

432
00:34:50,674 --> 00:34:52,676
Didn't think you were the type.

433
00:35:02,060 --> 00:35:04,062
It's backwards.

434
00:35:05,105 --> 00:35:07,774
Come here. Come here.

435
00:35:29,379 --> 00:35:31,381
What about here?

436
00:35:32,966 --> 00:35:35,385
Maybe it's… for when I find him.

437
00:35:37,971 --> 00:35:40,724
I've lost somebody too.

438
00:35:42,017 --> 00:35:44,019
I'm sorry.

439
00:35:44,144 --> 00:35:46,021
His name was Jimmy.

440
00:35:46,104 --> 00:35:48,482
- What happened to him?
- He went to meet somebody.

441
00:35:49,358 --> 00:35:51,527
He never came back.

442
00:35:52,611 --> 00:35:55,656
- Who did he go to meet?
- A guy called Teddy.

443
00:35:56,532 --> 00:35:58,575
What do the police think?

444
00:35:58,867 --> 00:36:02,579
They don't look too hard
for guys like Jimmy.

445
00:36:03,247 --> 00:36:05,916
When you find this guy, this…

446
00:36:06,041 --> 00:36:09,253
… John G, what are you gonna do?

447
00:36:11,713 --> 00:36:13,715
I'm gonna kill him.

448
00:36:15,509 --> 00:36:18,303
Maybe I can help you find him.

449
00:36:22,474 --> 00:36:26,186
I don't even know how long
she's been gone.

450
00:36:29,314 --> 00:36:32,985
It's like I've woken up in bed
and she's not here…

451
00:36:34,736 --> 00:36:38,866
… because she's gone to the bathroom
or something.

452
00:36:42,160 --> 00:36:44,580
But somehow I just…

453
00:36:45,372 --> 00:36:49,668
I just know
she's never gonna come back to bed.

454
00:36:53,672 --> 00:36:55,716
If I could just…

455
00:36:56,091 --> 00:36:59,845
… reach over
and touch her side of the bed,…

456
00:37:01,138 --> 00:37:03,932
… I would know that it was cold.

457
00:37:06,226 --> 00:37:08,437
But I can't.

458
00:37:12,107 --> 00:37:14,151
I know I can't have her back.

459
00:37:16,111 --> 00:37:20,866
But I don't want to wake up in the morning
thinking she's still here.

460
00:37:21,450 --> 00:37:25,954
I lie here not knowing
how long I've been alone.

461
00:37:31,835 --> 00:37:33,837
So how…

462
00:37:34,505 --> 00:37:36,590
How can I heal?

463
00:37:39,092 --> 00:37:42,179
How am I supposed to heal if I can't…

464
00:37:43,055 --> 00:37:45,140
… feel time?

465
00:38:57,254 --> 00:39:01,967
She has also lost someone.
She will help you out ofpity.

466
00:39:27,075 --> 00:39:29,870
They kept testing Sammy for months.

467
00:39:29,995 --> 00:39:32,915
Always with the same objects
carrying the electrical charge.

468
00:39:33,081 --> 00:39:35,083
- <font color="#40a040">[buzz]</font>
- Ow! What the fuck?

469
00:39:35,209 --> 00:39:37,586
- It's a test, Sammy.
- Test this, you fucking quack!

470
00:39:37,711 --> 00:39:39,755
Even with total short-term memory loss,…

471
00:39:39,880 --> 00:39:43,217
… Sammy should have learned instinctively
to stop picking up the wrong objects.

472
00:39:43,300 --> 00:39:47,346
Other cases responded to conditioning,
Sammy didn't respond at all.

473
00:39:47,429 --> 00:39:51,016
It suggested that his condition
was psychological not physical.

474
00:39:51,099 --> 00:39:55,646
We turned down his claim on the grounds
that he wasn't covered for mental illness.

475
00:39:55,771 --> 00:39:59,233
His wife got stuck with the bills
and I got a big promotion.

476
00:39:59,942 --> 00:40:03,862
Conditioning didn't work for Sammy,
so he became helpless.

477
00:40:03,987 --> 00:40:05,989
But it works for me.

478
00:40:06,114 --> 00:40:08,158
I live the way Sammy couldn't.

479
00:40:08,283 --> 00:40:10,744
Habit and routine make my life possible.

480
00:40:10,869 --> 00:40:13,622
Conditioning. Acting on instinct.

